AI-Assisted Predictive Hardware Health Monitoring for Medical Devices

Architecture and Technical Description

⸻

1. Overview

The proposed invention introduces an AI-assisted predictive hardware health monitoring framework for modular medical devices containing embedded electronic subsystems such as:

* System-on-Module (SOM)
* Main Control Board (MCB)
* Flip-Up Display (FUD)
* Embedded communication interfaces
* Sensor and power management modules

The invention continuously monitors subsystem operational behavior, detects abnormal degradation trends, generates subsystem-wise health scores, and provides preventive maintenance recommendations before complete subsystem failure occurs.

The framework is intended as a non-clinical advisory maintenance and reliability monitoring system and does not directly control therapy delivery or patient-critical functionality.

⸻

2. Problem Statement

Current medical devices primarily rely on reactive fault detection methods such as:

* Static alarms
* Hardware watchdogs
* Threshold violations
* Post-failure diagnostics
* Manual troubleshooting

These approaches detect failures only after visible malfunction occurs and are unable to identify gradual subsystem degradation patterns including:

* Increasing communication retries
* Response latency drift
* Thermal instability
* Voltage fluctuation
* Intermittent disconnect events
* Progressive hardware degradation

As a result:

* Unexpected downtime occurs
* Service cost increases
* Troubleshooting becomes difficult
* Reliability decreases
* Preventive maintenance becomes limited

There is currently a need for intelligent predictive subsystem health monitoring within modular medical devices.

⸻

3. Proposed Solution

The invention introduces a predictive maintenance framework capable of:

* Continuously collecting subsystem operational metrics
* Detecting abnormal subsystem behavior
* Identifying progressive degradation trends
* Correlating multiple subsystem operational parameters
* Generating operational health scores
* Predicting possible future subsystem degradation
* Generating preventive maintenance recommendations

The framework combines:

* Rule-based monitoring
* AI-assisted anomaly detection
* Time-series trend analysis
* Embedded subsystem diagnostics

