5. Detailed Component Description

5.1 Metric Collection Engine

The metric collection engine continuously gathers operational subsystem parameters from embedded medical device hardware and software components.

Example Metrics

SOM Metrics

* CPU temperature
* CPU utilization
* Memory usage
* Thermal throttling events
* Kernel errors
* Reset count

MCB Metrics

* Voltage rails
* Current consumption
* Communication heartbeat
* Sensor communication status
* Firmware operational state

FUD Metrics

* Communication retry count
* Display response latency
* Display initialization time
* Disconnect events
* Flip sensor status

The metrics are collected periodically at configurable intervals and stored locally for trend analysis.

⸻

5.2 Local Data Storage Layer

The collected metrics are stored using:

* SQLite database
* Embedded storage engine
* Local logging framework
* Time-series storage mechanisms

The storage layer maintains historical operational data required for:

* Trend analysis
* Degradation prediction
* Anomaly detection
* Diagnostic reporting

⸻

5.3 Rule-Based Health Engine

The rule engine evaluates subsystem operational thresholds and predefined diagnostic rules.



If CPU temperature exceeds threshold:
Raise thermal warning

If communication retry count increases:
Raise communication degradation alert

If voltage fluctuation exceeds allowable range:
Raise power instability warning



The rule engine provides deterministic subsystem monitoring and first-level fault evaluation.



5.4 AI-Based Anomaly Detection Engine

The anomaly detection engine identifies abnormal subsystem operational behavior using historical metric analysis and AI-assisted monitoring.

Possible techniques include:

* Isolation Forest
* Statistical anomaly detection
* Time-series trend analysis
* Random Forest
* XGBoost

The AI engine detects:

* Progressive degradation patterns
* Correlated subsystem instability
* Thermal drift
* Abnormal retry behavior
* Latency variation trends
* Intermittent disconnect conditions

⸻

